Banker’s Algorithm is a resource allocation and deadlock avoidance algorithm used in operating systems. It ensures that the system never enters an unsafe state by carefully analyzing resource allocation before granting requests.
The algorithm simulates resource allocation for each process and checks whether all processes can complete their execution safely without causing a deadlock.
Theory:
The algorithm uses the following data structures:
Allocation Matrix: Resources currently allocated to each process
Max Matrix: Maximum demand of each process
Need Matrix: Remaining resources required (Max - Allocation)
Available Vector: Resources currently available in the system
Finish Array: Tracks whether a process has completed execution
Work Vector: Temporary copy of available resources
A system is considered safe if there exists a sequence of processes such that all processes can execute completely without causing deadlock.
Algorithm Steps:
Input number of processes and resources
Input Allocation matrix
Input Max matrix
Input Available resources
Compute Need matrix
Initialize Work = Available and Finish = false
Find a process whose Need ≤ Work
Allocate resources temporarily and mark process as finished
Repeat until all processes are finished or no safe sequence exists
If all processes finish → system is safe
